law.text:
Except as otherwise provided in § 9-624, to the extent that they give rights to a debtor or obligor and impose duties on a secured party, the debtor or obligor may not waive or vary the rules stated in the following listed sections:
§ 9-207(b)(4)(C), which deals with use and operation of the collateral by the secured party;
§ 9-210, which deals with requests for an accounting and requests concerning a list of collateral and statement of account;
§ 9-607(c), which deals with collection and enforcement of collateral;
§§ 9-608(a) and 9-615(c) to the extent that they deal with application or payment of noncash proceeds of collection, enforcement, or disposition;
§§ 9-608(a) and 9-615(d) to the extent that they require accounting for or payment of surplus proceeds of collateral;
§ 9-609 to the extent that it imposes upon a secured party that takes possession of collateral without judicial process the duty to do so without breach of the peace;
§§ 9-610(b), 9-611, 9-613, and 9-614, which deal with disposition of collateral;
§ 9-615(f), which deals with calculation of a deficiency or surplus when a disposition is made to the secured party, a person related to the secured party, or a secondary obligor;
§ 9-616, which deals with explanation of the calculation of a surplus or deficiency;
§§ 9-620, 9-621, and 9-622, which deal with acceptance of collateral in satisfaction of obligation;
§ 9-623, which deals with redemption of collateral;
§ 9-624, which deals with permissible waivers; and
§§ 9-625 and 9-626, which deal with the secured party's liability for failure to comply with this article.
